metadata.name: Why? #4
metadata.description:
The direction taken by the artwork Why? was taken when contemplating a canvas filled with what could be viewed as huge stone steps. I added the small stick people - were they climbing up or down? Where were they going? Where did they come from?
I then became interested in how subtle changes of background colour and changes of balloon colour changed the story, or the feeling of the story - ranging from bright hope to despair and futility. 

All p5.js.
The artwork is rendered at window size, use keys '2' and '3' to render larger.

metadata.name: Imperium #66
metadata.description:
Imperium is a study of shapes and colors, and how a very small set of shapes and colors, when given equally simple rules, can create a great variety of patterns that may bring meaning to the viewer.

metadata.name: Landscapes out of my mind #238
metadata.description:
In this work, the third in the series of landscapes, I tried to achieve greater realism without abandoning those elements, also characteristic of the other works, which lead out of reality such as the shapes of the ground and trees and the choice of palettes.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with space colonization algorithm an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density is driven by the land heightmap.


Developed with three.js using WebGLRenderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.


[s] to save a png at 2048x1536, 1536x2048, 2048x2048 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)
[d] to save a png at 4096x3072, 3072x4096, 4096x4096 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)


Features:
"Palette": 14 colormaps
"Aspect Ratio": 4/3, 3/4, 4/4
"View Point":  Far, Medium, Near, Above
"Sky Type": FBM, Gradient1, Gradient2
"Sky Color": LightSkyBlue, Gray, Blue [10% probability]
"Bark Color":  Brown, GrayBrown, Gray
"Bare Trees": True, False


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Coronado #303
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: Zhu(竹) #43
metadata.description:
Zhu(竹):

"Zhu" is a series of 100 oriental abstract pieces featuring the imagery of bamboo, a symbol of integrity and strength in traditional Chinese culture.

Zhu's generative system is an exploration of this cultural symbol by modern art language. Elements of the paintings are merely circles, enclosed flow field shapes, and the blank space behind these visual objects. Blank-leaving is intentionally applied at various degrees throughout the series. The vast empty space beyond the plants is open to and embraces every kind of interpretation.

Zhu's outputs span hours of the day from dawn to dusk to night. Its color schemes explored four styles from traditional to modern. The simple yet complex senses and feelings reflected are surprisingly versatile.

metadata.name: ASCII-SCAPE #219
metadata.description:
ASCII-SCAPE

Like for many others growing up during the 1980s & 90s, my very first hands-on encounter with actual computer graphics (outside of games) was in the form of "textmode" and its various alphanumeric characters and other symbols available on the 8bit home computers of that period. These machines were perfectly capable of producing fairly high-resolution & multi-color graphics (all relative), yet most systems booted into an interactive prompt with the so-called textmode as de-facto standard environment, providing a level, if also limited, playing field for the creation of text-based graphics from a patchwork of characters & symbols of a predefined font (system or custom). As is so often the case, limitation is the mother of invention and the regular, monospaced grid and standardized set of characters quickly encouraged an entire subculture of specialized designers & artists to emerge (which is currently being re-discovered & remixed by younger generations), applying & showcasing their creativity (with often surprisingly ingenious skills) in the form of game designs, user interfaces, disk mags, demoscene productions, competitions, flyers, BBSes and even various early Web designs of the mid/late 90s.

ASCII-SCAPE is an attempted non-nostalgic homage to these roots & culture. It is also a textmode-only (no canvas!) rework of my previous piece C-SCAPE. It combines my love of cellular automata with the stripped back aesthetics & limitations of using only text as representation medium of these co-evolving generative systems. It required an almost complete rewrite & re-curation of various elements: 1200+ new handpicked rule combinations, 32 character sets, 40 color themes, new relationships & biases to better manage the resulting textures, densities and contrast.

Although technically not strictly "ASCII" (an actual standard, but also a popular shorthand for "text only"), the entire simulation only uses various Unicode characters and the beautiful Iosevka open source typeface by Renzhi Li aka Belleve Invis.

Like its parent C-SCAPE, this project is dynamic and evolves indefinitely. It's best viewed on non-mobile devices, where there's a decent horizontal resolution to provide sufficient simulation space. Please see the C-SCAPE project description for further details. There's no graphical export feature, but output can be captured into an UTF-8 plain text file (max. 100k lines/generations).

The following keyboard shortcuts are available:

- space : toggle simulation updates (pause/play)
- r : randomize environment
- x : start/stop recording
- f : toggle scroll speed (fast/slow)

License

https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/

Iosevka typeface licensed under OFL-1.1 license

https://github.com/be5invis/Iosevka

Disclaimer

Minting this project will not guarantee inclusion in access lists for future projects.

Credits

metadata.name: Modern Times #146
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Sixty# #82
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Geode #80
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #73
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js
